# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wave-mechanics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] In the physical sciences and electrical engineering, **dispersion relations** describe the effect of dispersion on the properties of waves in a medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] A dispersion relation relates the wavelength or wavenumber of a wave to its frequency.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Given the dispersion relation, one can calculate the frequency-dependent phase velocity and group velocity of each sinusoidal component of a wave in the medium, as a function of frequency.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] In addition to the geometry-dependent and material-dependent dispersion relations, the overarching Kramers–Kronig relations describe the frequency-dependence of wave propagation and attenuation.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Dispersion may be caused either by geometric boundary conditions (waveguides, shallow water) or by interaction of the waves with the transmitting medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Elementary particles, considered as matter waves, have a nontrivial dispersion relation, even in the absence of geometric constraints and other media.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] In the presence of dispersion, a wave does not propagate with an unchanging waveform, giving rise to the distinct frequency-dependent phase velocity and group velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Dispersion occurs when sinusoidal waves of different wavelengths have different propagation velocities, so that a wave packet of mixed wavelengths tends to spread out in space.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The function $f(\lambda )$ expresses the dispersion relation of the given medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Dispersion relations are more commonly expressed in terms of the angular frequency $\omega =2\pi f$ and wavenumber $k=2\pi /\lambda$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] where we now view *f* as a function of *k*.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The use of *ω*(*k*) to describe the dispersion relation has become standard because both the phase velocity *ω*/*k* and the group velocity *dω*/*dk* have convenient representations via this function.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Plane waves in vacuum are the simplest case of wave propagation: no geometric constraint, no interaction with a transmitting medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] This is a *linear* dispersion relation, in which case the waves are said to be **non-dispersive**.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] That is, the phase velocity and the group velocity are the same: $v={\frac {\omega }{k}}={\frac {d\omega }{dk}}=c,$ and thus both are equal to the speed of light in vacuum, which is frequency-independent.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The variation has two parts: a constant part due to the de Broglie frequency of the rest mass ( $\hbar \omega _{0}=m_{0}c^{2}$ ) and a quadratic part due to kinetic energy.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] While applications of matter waves occur at non-relativistic velocity, de Broglie applied special relativity to derive his waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Divide by $\hbar$ and take the square root.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Practical work with matter waves occurs at non-relativistic velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Then we see that the $\hbar /c$ factor is very small so for k not too large, we expand ${\sqrt {1+x^{2}}}\approx 1+x^{2}/2,$ and multiply: $\omega (k)\approx {\frac {m_{0}c^{2}}{\hbar }}+{\frac {\hbar k^{2}}{2m_{0}}}\,.$ This gives the non-relativistic approximation discussed above.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] If we start with the non-relativistic Schrödinger equation we will end up without the first, rest mass, term.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] As mentioned above, when the focus in a medium is on refraction rather than absorption—that is, on the real part of the refractive index—it is common to refer to the functional dependence of angular frequency on wavenumber as the *dispersion relation*.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] For particles, this translates to a knowledge of energy as a function of momentum.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The name "dispersion relation" originally comes from optics.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] It is possible to make the effective speed of light dependent on wavelength by making light pass through a material which has a non-constant index of refraction, or by using light in a non-uniform medium such as a waveguide.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] In this case, the waveform will spread over time, such that a narrow pulse will become an extended pulse, i.e., be dispersed.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] In these materials, ${\frac {\partial \omega }{\partial k}}$ is known as the group velocity and corresponds to the speed at which the peak of the pulse propagates, a value different from the phase velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] where *g* is the acceleration due to gravity.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Deep water, in this respect, is commonly denoted as the case where the water depth is larger than half the wavelength.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] where *T* is the tension force in the string, and *μ* is the string's mass per unit length.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] As for the case of electromagnetic waves in vacuum, ideal strings are thus a non-dispersive medium, i.e. the phase and group velocities are equal and independent (to first order) of vibration frequency.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] where $\alpha$ is a constant that depends on the string.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] In the study of solids, the study of the dispersion relation of electrons is of paramount importance.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The periodicity of crystals means that many levels of energy are possible for a given momentum and that some energies might not be available at any momentum.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The collection of all possible energies and momenta is known as the band structure of a material.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Properties of the band structure define whether the material is an insulator, semiconductor or conductor.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Phonons are to sound waves in a solid what photons are to light: they are the quanta that carry it.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The dispersion relation of phonons is also non-trivial and important, being directly related to the acoustic and thermal properties of a material.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] For most systems, the phonons can be categorized into two main types: those whose bands become zero at the center of the Brillouin zone are called acoustic phonons, since they correspond to classical sound in the limit of long wavelengths.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The others are optical phonons, since they can be excited by electromagnetic radiation.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] This dynamical effect has found application in the precise measurement of lattice parameters, beam energy, and more recently for the electronics industry: lattice strain.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Isaac Newton studied refraction in prisms but failed to recognize the material dependence of the dispersion relation, dismissing the work of another researcher whose measurement of a prism's dispersion did not match Newton's own.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] Dispersion of waves on water was studied by Pierre-Simon Laplace in 1776.
[src:wave-mechanics/dispersion-relation] The universality of the Kramers–Kronig relations (1926–27) became apparent with subsequent papers on the dispersion relation's connection to causality in the scattering theory of all types of waves and particles.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The **group velocity** of a wave is the velocity with which the overall envelope shape of the wave's amplitudes—known as the *modulation* or *envelope* of the wave—propagates through space.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] For example, if a stone is thrown into the middle of a very still pond, a circular pattern of waves with a quiescent center appears in the water, also known as a capillary wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The expanding ring of waves is the **wave group** or wave packet, within which one can discern individual waves that travel faster than the group as a whole.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The amplitudes of the individual waves grow as they emerge from the trailing edge of the group and diminish as they approach the leading edge of the group.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The idea of a group velocity distinct from a wave's phase velocity was first proposed by W.R.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Hamilton in 1839, and the first full treatment was by Rayleigh in his "Theory of Sound" in 1877.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Consider a linear evolution model of waves that admits as fundamental solutions the oscillators ${\textstyle e^{i(kx-\omega t)}}$ , where k and $\omega$ are bound to satisfy a certain constraint.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] satisfies the above description with $\omega ={\frac {\hbar }{2m}}k^{2}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Here, *ω* is the wave's angular frequency (usually expressed in radians per second), and *k* is the angular wavenumber (usually expressed in radians per meter).
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The function *ω*(*k*), which gives *ω* as a function of *k*, is known as the dispersion relation.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] One derivation of the formula for group velocity is as follows.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Consider a wave packet as a function of position *x* and time *t*: *α*(*x*,*t*).
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] By the superposition principle, the wavepacket at any time *t* is $\alpha (x,t)=\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }dk\,A(k)e^{i(kx-\omega t)},$ where *ω* is implicitly a function of *k*.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Assume that the wave packet *α* is almost monochromatic, so that *A*(*k*) is sharply peaked around a central wavenumber *k*0.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] There are two factors in this expression.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The first factor, $e^{i\left(k_{0}x-\omega _{0}t\right)}$ , describes a perfect monochromatic wave with wavevector *k*0, with peaks and troughs moving at the phase velocity $\omega _{0}/k_{0}$ within the envelope of the wavepacket.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] This envelope function depends on position and time *only* through the combination $(x-\omega '_{0}t)$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Therefore, the envelope of the wavepacket travels at velocity $\omega '_{0}=\left.{\frac {d\omega }{dk}}\right|_{k=k_{0}}~,$ which explains the group velocity formula.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] If the wavepacket has a relatively large frequency spread, or if the dispersion *ω(k)* has sharp variations (such as due to a resonance), or if the packet travels over very long distances, this assumption is not valid, and higher-order terms in the Taylor expansion become important.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] As a result, the envelope of the wave packet not only moves, but also *distorts,* in a manner that can be described by the material's group velocity dispersion.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Loosely speaking, different frequency-components of the wavepacket travel at different speeds, with the faster components moving towards the front of the wavepacket and the slower moving towards the back.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Eventually, the wave packet gets stretched out.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] This is an important effect in the propagation of signals through optical fibers and in the design of high-power, short-pulse lasers.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] In the context of electromagnetics and optics, the frequency is some function *ω*(*k*) of the wave number, so in general, the phase velocity and the group velocity depend on specific medium and frequency.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The ratio between the speed of light *c* and the phase velocity *v**p* is known as the refractive index, *n* = *c* / *v**p* = *ck* / *ω*.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] In this way, we can obtain another form for group velocity for electromagnetics.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] From this formula, we see that the group velocity is equal to the phase velocity only when the refractive index is independent of frequency ${\textstyle \partial n/\partial \omega =0}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] When this occurs, the medium is called non-dispersive, as opposed to dispersive, where various properties of the medium depend on the frequency ω.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The relation $\omega (k)$ is known as the dispersion relation of the medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] where ${\vec {\nabla }}_{\mathbf {k} }\,\omega$ means the gradient of the angular frequency ω as a function of the wave vector $\mathbf {k}$ , and ${\hat {\mathbf {k} }}$ is the unit vector in direction **k**.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] If the waves are propagating through an anisotropic (i.e., not rotationally symmetric) medium, for example a crystal, then the phase velocity vector and group velocity vector may point in different directions.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The group velocity is often thought of as the velocity at which energy or information is conveyed along a wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] In most cases this is accurate, and the group velocity can be thought of as the signal velocity of the waveform.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] However, if the wave is travelling through an absorptive or gainful medium, this does not always hold.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] In these cases the group velocity may not be a well-defined quantity, or may not be a meaningful quantity.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] In his text "Wave Propagation in Periodic Structures", Brillouin argued that in a lossy medium the group velocity ceases to have a clear physical meaning.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] An example concerning the transmission of electromagnetic waves through an atomic gas is given by Loudon.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Another example is mechanical waves in the solar photosphere: The waves are damped (by radiative heat flow from the peaks to the troughs), and related to that, the energy velocity is often substantially lower than the waves' group velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Despite this ambiguity, a common way to extend the concept of group velocity to complex media is to consider spatially damped plane wave solutions inside the medium, which are characterized by a *complex-valued* wavevector.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] It can be shown that this generalization of group velocity continues to be related to the apparent speed of the peak of a wavepacket.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The above definition is not universal, however: alternatively one may consider the time damping of standing waves (real k, complex ω), or, allow group velocity to be a complex-valued quantity.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Different considerations yield distinct velocities, yet all definitions agree for the case of a lossless, gainless medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The above generalization of group velocity for complex media can behave strangely, and the example of anomalous dispersion serves as a good illustration.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] At the edges of a region of anomalous dispersion, $v_{\text{g}}$ becomes infinite (surpassing even the speed of light in vacuum), and $v_{\text{g}}$ may easily become negative (its sign opposes Rek) inside the band of anomalous dispersion.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Since the 1980s, various experiments have verified that it is possible for the group velocity (as defined above) of laser light pulses sent through lossy materials, or gainful materials, to significantly exceed the speed of light in vacuum c.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] The peaks of wavepackets were also seen to move faster than c.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] In all these cases, however, there is no possibility that signals could be carried faster than the speed of light in vacuum, since the high value of vg does not help to speed up the true motion of the sharp wavefront that would occur at the start of any real signal.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] Essentially the seemingly superluminal transmission is an artifact of the narrow band approximation used above to define group velocity and happens because of resonance phenomena in the intervening medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/group-velocity] In a wide band analysis it is seen that the apparently paradoxical speed of propagation of the signal envelope is actually the result of local interference of a wider band of frequencies over many cycles, all of which propagate perfectly causally and at phase velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/phase-velocity] The **phase velocity** of a wave is the speed of any wavefront, a surface of constant phase.
[src:wave-mechanics/phase-velocity] This is the velocity at which the phase of any constant-frequency component of the wave travels.
[src:wave-mechanics/phase-velocity] For such a spectral component, any given phase of the wave (for example, the crest) will appear to travel at the phase velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/phase-velocity] The phase velocity of light waves is not a physically meaningful quantity and is not related to information transfer.
[src:wave-mechanics/phase-velocity] The previous definition of phase velocity has been demonstrated for an isolated wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/phase-velocity] However, such a definition can be extended to a beat of waves, or to a signal composed of multiple waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/phase-velocity] For this it is necessary to mathematically write the beat or signal as a low frequency envelope multiplying a carrier.
[src:wave-mechanics/phase-velocity] Thus the phase velocity of the carrier determines the phase velocity of the wave set.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] In physics, a **plane wave** is a special case of a wave or field: a physical quantity whose value, at any given moment, is constant through any plane that is perpendicular to a fixed direction in space.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] The displacement is constant over each plane perpendicular to ${\vec {n}}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] The values of the field F may be scalars, vectors, or any other physical or mathematical quantity.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] They can be complex numbers, as in a complex exponential plane wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] When the values of F are vectors, the wave is said to be a longitudinal wave if the vectors are always collinear with the vector ${\vec {n}}$ , and a transverse wave if they are always orthogonal (perpendicular) to it.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] Often the term "plane wave" refers specifically to a *traveling plane wave*, whose evolution in time can be described as simple translation of the field at a constant *wave speed* c along the direction perpendicular to the wavefronts.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] In that case, ${\vec {n}}$ is called the *direction of propagation*.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] For each displacement d , the moving plane perpendicular to ${\vec {n}}$ at distance $d+ct$ from the origin is called a "wavefront".
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] These planes travel along the direction of propagation ${\vec {n}}$ with velocity c ; and the value of the field is then the same, and constant in time, at every one of their points.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] The term is also used, even more specifically, to mean a "monochromatic" or sinusoidal plane wave: a travelling plane wave whose profile $G(u)$ is a sinusoidal function.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] That is, $F({\vec {x}},t)=A\sin \left(2\pi f({\vec {x}}\cdot {\vec {n}}-ct)+\varphi \right)$ The parameter A , which may be a scalar or a vector, is called the amplitude of the wave; the scalar coefficient f is its "spatial frequency"; and the scalar $\varphi$ is its "phase shift".
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] A true plane wave cannot physically exist, because it would have to fill all space.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] Nevertheless, the plane wave model is important and widely used in physics.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] The waves emitted by any source with finite extent into a large homogeneous region of space can be well approximated by plane waves when viewed over any part of that region that is sufficiently small compared to its distance from the source.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] That is the case, for example, of the light waves from a distant star that arrive at a telescope.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] A standing wave is a field whose value can be expressed as the product of two functions, one depending only on position, the other only on time.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] A plane standing wave, in particular, can be expressed as $F({\vec {x}},t)=G({\vec {x}}\cdot {\vec {n}})\,S(t)$ where G is a function of one scalar parameter (the displacement $d={\vec {x}}\cdot {\vec {n}}$ ) with scalar or vector values, and S is a scalar function of time.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] This representation is not unique, since the same field values are obtained if S and G are scaled by reciprocal factors.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] If $\left|S(t)\right|$ is bounded in the time interval of interest (which is usually the case in physical contexts), S and G can be scaled so that the maximum value of $\left|S(t)\right|$ is 1.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] Then $\left|G({\vec {x}}\cdot {\vec {n}})\right|$ will be the maximum field magnitude seen at the point ${\vec {x}}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] A plane wave can be studied by ignoring the directions perpendicular to the direction vector ${\vec {n}}$ ; that is, by considering the function $G(z,t)=F(z{\vec {n}},t)$ as a wave in a one-dimensional medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] Any local operator, linear or not, applied to a plane wave yields a plane wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] Any linear combination of plane waves with the same normal vector ${\vec {n}}$ is also a plane wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/plane-wave] The divergence of a vector-valued plane wave depends only on the projection of the vector $G(d,t)$ in the direction ${\vec {n}}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The **wave equation** is a second-order linear partial differential equation for the description of waves or standing wave fields such as mechanical waves (e.g. water waves, sound waves and seismic waves) or electromagnetic waves (including light waves).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] It arises in fields like acoustics, electromagnetism, and fluid dynamics.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This article focuses on waves in classical physics.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Quantum physics uses an operator-based wave equation often as a relativistic wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The wave equation is a hyperbolic partial differential equation describing waves, including traveling and standing waves; the latter can be considered as linear superpositions of waves traveling in opposite directions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This article mostly focuses on the scalar wave equation describing waves in scalars by scalar functions $u=u(x,y,z,t)$ of a time variable t (a variable representing time) and one or more spatial variables $x,y,z$ (variables representing a position in a space under discussion).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] At the same time, there are vector wave equations describing waves in vectors such as waves for an electrical field, magnetic field, and magnetic vector potential and elastic waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] For example, in the Cartesian coordinate system, for $(E_{x},E_{y},E_{z})$ as the representation of an electric vector field wave ${\vec {E}}$ in the absence of wave sources, each coordinate axis component $E_{i},i=x,y,z,$ must satisfy the scalar wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Other scalar wave equation solutions u are for physical quantities in scalars such as pressure in a liquid or gas, or the displacement along some specific direction of particles of a vibrating solid away from their resting (equilibrium) positions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The equation states that, at any given point, the second derivative of u with respect to time is proportional to the sum of the second derivatives of u with respect to space, with the constant of proportionality being the square of the speed of the wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] A solution to this (two-way) wave equation can be quite complicated.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Still, it can be analyzed as a linear combination of simple solutions that are sinusoidal plane waves with various directions of propagation and wavelengths but all with the same propagation speed c .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This analysis is possible because the wave equation is linear and homogeneous, so that any multiple of a solution is also a solution, and the sum of any two solutions is again a solution.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This property is called the superposition principle in physics.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The wave equation alone does not specify a physical solution; a unique solution is usually obtained by setting a problem with further conditions, such as initial conditions, which prescribe the amplitude and phase of the wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Another important class of problems occurs in enclosed spaces specified by boundary conditions, for which the solutions represent standing waves, or harmonics, analogous to the harmonics of musical instruments.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The wave equation in one spatial dimension can be written as follows: ${\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial t^{2}}}=c^{2}{\frac {\partial ^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}}.$ This equation is typically described as having only one spatial dimension x , because the only other independent variable is the time t .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The wave equation in one space dimension can be derived in a variety of different physical settings.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Most famously, it can be derived for the case of a string vibrating in a two-dimensional plane, with each of its elements being pulled in opposite directions by the force of tension.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Another physical setting for derivation of the wave equation in one space dimension uses Hooke's law.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In the theory of elasticity, Hooke's law is an approximation for certain materials, stating that the amount by which a material body is deformed (the strain) is linearly related to the force causing the deformation (the stress).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The wave equation in the one-dimensional case can be derived from Hooke's law in the following way: imagine an array of little weights of mass m interconnected with massless springs of length ⁠ h ⁠.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Here the dependent variable $u(x)$ measures the horizontal displacement from equilibrium of the mass situated at ⁠ x ⁠, so that $u(x)$ essentially measures the magnitude of a disturbance (i.e. strain) that is traveling in an elastic material.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In the case of a stress pulse propagating longitudinally through a bar, the bar acts much like an infinite number of springs in series and can be taken as an extension of the equation derived for Hooke's law.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] A uniform bar, i.e. of constant cross-section, made from a linear elastic material has a stiffness K given by $K={\frac {EA}{L}},$ where A is the cross-sectional area, and E is the Young's modulus of the material.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] $AL$ is equal to the volume of the bar, and therefore ${\frac {AL}{M}}={\frac {1}{\rho }},$ where $\rho$ is the density of the material.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The speed of a stress wave in a bar is therefore ${\sqrt {E/\rho }}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] For the one-dimensional wave equation a relatively simple general solution may be found.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In other words, the solution is the sum of a right-traveling function F and a left-traveling function G .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] "Traveling" means that the shape of these individual arbitrary functions with respect to x stays constant, however, the functions are translated left and right with time at the speed c .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This was derived by Jean le Rond d'Alembert.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This advection equation can be solved by interpreting it as telling us that the directional derivative of v in the $(1,-c)$ direction is 0.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This means that the value of v is constant on characteristic lines of the form *x* + *ct* = *x*0, and thus that v must depend only on *x* + *ct*, that is, have the form *H*(*x* + *ct*).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Then, to solve the first (inhomogenous) equation relating v to u, we can note that its homogenous solution must be a function of the form *F*(*x* - *ct*), by logic similar to the above.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This means we can find a particular solution *G* of the desired form by integration.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] However, the waveforms F and G may also be generalized functions, such as the delta-function.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In that case, the solution may be interpreted as an impulse that travels to the right or the left.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The basic wave equation is a linear differential equation, and so it will adhere to the superposition principle.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This means that the net displacement caused by two or more waves is the sum of the displacements which would have been caused by each wave individually.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In addition, the behavior of a wave can be analyzed by breaking up the wave into components, e.g. the Fourier transform breaks up a wave into sinusoidal components.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Another way to solve the one-dimensional wave equation is to first analyze its frequency eigenmodes.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Known as the Helmholtz equation, it has the well-known plane-wave solutions $f(x)=Ae^{\pm ikx},$ with wave number *k* = *ω*/*c*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The total wave function for this eigenmode is then the linear combination $u_{\omega }(x,t)=e^{-i\omega t}\left(Ae^{-ikx}+Be^{ikx}\right)=Ae^{-i(kx+\omega t)}+Be^{i(kx-\omega t)},$ where complex numbers A, B depend in general on any initial and boundary conditions of the problem.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Functions *s*±(*ω*) are known as the Fourier component and are determined by initial and boundary conditions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This is a so-called frequency-domain method, alternative to direct time-domain propagations, such as FDTD method, of the wave packet *u*(*x*, *t*), which is complete for representing waves in absence of time dilations.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Completeness of the Fourier expansion for representing waves in the presence of time dilations has been challenged by chirp wave solutions allowing for time variation of ω.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The vectorial wave equation (from which the scalar wave equation can be directly derived) can be obtained by applying a force equilibrium to an infinitesimal volume element.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] If the medium has a modulus of elasticity E that is homogeneous (i.e. independent of $\mathbf {x}$ ) within the volume element, then its stress tensor is given by $\mathbf {T} =E\nabla \mathbf {u}$ , for a vectorial elastic deflection $\mathbf {u} (\mathbf {x} ,t)$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] By merging density $\rho$ and elasticity module $E,$ the sound velocity $c={\sqrt {E/\rho }}$ results (material law).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The above vectorial partial differential equation of the 2nd order delivers two mutually independent solutions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] From the quadratic velocity term $c^{2}=(+c)^{2}=(-c)^{2}$ can be seen that there are two waves travelling in opposite directions $+c$ and $-c$ are possible, hence results the designation "two-way wave equation".
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] It can be shown for plane longitudinal wave propagation that the synthesis of two one-way wave equations leads to a general two-way wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] A solution of the initial-value problem for the wave equation in three space dimensions can be obtained from the corresponding solution for a spherical wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The result can then be also used to obtain the same solution in two space dimensions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This is the Helmholtz equation and can be solved using separation of variables.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Then there is no angular dependence and the amplitude depends only on the radial distance, i.e., Ψ(**r**, *t*) → *u*(*r*, *t*).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This equation can be rewritten as ${\frac {\partial ^{2}(ru)}{\partial t^{2}}}-c^{2}{\frac {\partial ^{2}(ru)}{\partial r^{2}}}=0,$ where the quantity *ru* satisfies the one-dimensional wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Therefore, there are solutions in the form $u(r,t)={\frac {1}{r}}F(r-ct)+{\frac {1}{r}}G(r+ct),$ where F and G are general solutions to the one-dimensional wave equation and can be interpreted as respectively an outgoing and incoming spherical waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The outgoing wave can be generated by a point source, and they make possible sharp signals whose form is altered only by a decrease in amplitude as r increases (see an illustration of a spherical wave on the top right).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Such waves exist only in cases of space with odd dimensions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] For physical examples of solutions to the 3D wave equation that possess angular dependence, see dipole radiation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Although the word "monochromatic" is not exactly accurate, since it refers to light or electromagnetic radiation with well-defined frequency, the spirit is to discover the eigenmode of the wave equation in three dimensions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] From this we can observe that the peak intensity of the spherical-wave oscillation, characterized as the squared wave amplitude $I=|u(r,t)|^{2}={\frac {|A|^{2}}{r^{2}}},$ drops at the rate proportional to 1/*r*2, an example of the inverse-square law.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The wave equation is linear in u and is left unaltered by translations in space and time.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Therefore, we can generate a great variety of solutions by translating and summing spherical waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Let *φ*(*ξ*, *η*, *ζ*) be an arbitrary function of three independent variables, and let the spherical wave form F be a delta function.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Let a family of spherical waves have center at (*ξ*, *η*, *ζ*), and let r be the radial distance from that point.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] If u is a superposition of such waves with weighting function φ, then $u(t,x,y,z)={\frac {1}{4\pi c}}\iiint \varphi (\xi ,\eta ,\zeta ){\frac {\delta (r-ct)}{r}}\,d\xi \,d\eta \,d\zeta ;$ the denominator 4*πc* is a convenience.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] From the definition of the delta function, u may also be written as $u(t,x,y,z)={\frac {t}{4\pi }}\iint _{S}\varphi (x+ct\alpha ,y+ct\beta ,z+ct\gamma )\,d\omega ,$ where α, β, and γ are coordinates on the unit sphere S, and ω is the area element on S.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] These formulas provide the solution for the initial-value problem for the wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] They show that the solution at a given point P, given (*t*, *x*, *y*, *z*) depends only on the data on the sphere of radius *ct* that is intersected by the **light cone** drawn backwards from P.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] It does *not* depend upon data on the interior of this sphere.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Thus the interior of the sphere is a lacuna for the solution.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This phenomenon is called **Huygens' principle**.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] It is only true for odd numbers of space dimension, where for one dimension the integration is performed over the boundary of an interval with respect to the Dirac measure.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] We can use the three-dimensional theory to solve this problem if we regard u as a function in three dimensions that is independent of the third dimension.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] where α and β are the first two coordinates on the unit sphere, and d*ω* is the area element on the sphere.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] It is apparent that the solution at (*t*, *x*, *y*) depends not only on the data on the light cone where $(x-\xi )^{2}+(y-\eta )^{2}=c^{2}t^{2},$ but also on data that are interior to that cone.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Consider the inhomogeneous wave equation in $1+D$ dimensions $(\partial _{tt}-c^{2}\nabla ^{2})u=s(t,x)$ By rescaling time, we can set wave speed $c=1$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Since the wave equation $(\partial _{tt}-\nabla ^{2})u=s(t,x)$ has order 2 in time, there are two impulse responses: an acceleration impulse and a velocity impulse.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The effect of inflicting an acceleration impulse is to suddenly change the wave velocity $\partial _{t}u$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The effect of inflicting a velocity impulse is to suddenly change the wave displacement u .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] For acceleration impulse, $s(t,x)=\delta ^{D+1}(t,x)$ where $\delta$ is the Dirac delta function.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The solution to this case is called the Green's function G for the wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] For velocity impulse, $s(t,x)=\partial _{t}\delta ^{D+1}(t,x)$ , so if we solve the Green function G , the solution for this case is just $\partial _{t}G$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The main use of Green's functions is to solve initial value problems by Duhamel's principle, both for the homogeneous and the inhomogeneous case.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Given the Green function G , and initial conditions $u(0,x),\partial _{t}u(0,x)$ , the solution to the homogeneous wave equation is $u=(\partial _{t}G)\ast u+G\ast \partial _{t}u$ where the asterisk is convolution in space.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] It would require us to perturb the integral slightly either by $+i\epsilon$ or by $-i\epsilon$ , because it is an improper integral.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] One perturbation gives the forward solution, and the other the backward solution.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] We can relate the Green's function in D dimensions to the Green's function in $D+n$ dimensions (lowering the dimension is possible in any case, raising is possible in spherical symmetry).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The Green's function in D dimensions can be related to the Green's function in $D+2$ dimensions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The dimension can be raised to give the $D=3$ case $G_{3}(t,r)={\frac {\delta (t-r)}{4\pi r}}$ and similarly for the backward solution.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In $D=1$ case, the Green's function solution is the sum of two wavefronts ${\frac {\operatorname {sgn}(t-x)}{4}}+{\frac {\operatorname {sgn}(t+x)}{4}}$ moving in opposite directions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In odd dimensions, the forward solution is nonzero only at $t=r$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] As the dimensions increase, the shape of wavefront becomes increasingly complex, involving higher derivatives of the Dirac delta function.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In even dimensions, the forward solution is nonzero in $r\leq t$ , the entire region behind the wavefront becomes nonzero, called a wake.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This means that a general Huygens' principle – the wave displacement at a point $(t,x)$ in spacetime depends only on the state at points on characteristic rays passing $(t,x)$ – only holds in odd dimensions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] A physical interpretation is that signals transmitted by waves remain undistorted in odd dimensions, but distorted in even dimensions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] For an incident wave traveling from one medium (where the wave speed is *c*1) to another medium (where the wave speed is *c*2), one part of the wave will transmit into the second medium, while another part reflects back into the other direction and stays in the first medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The amplitude of the transmitted wave and the reflected wave can be calculated by using the continuity condition at the boundary.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Consider the component of the incident wave with an angular frequency of ω, which has the waveform $u^{\text{inc}}(x,t)=Ae^{i(k_{1}x-\omega t)},\quad A\in \mathbb {C} .$ At *t* = 0, the incident reaches the boundary between the two media at *x* = 0.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The energy conservation can be verified by ${\frac {B^{2}}{c_{1}}}+{\frac {C^{2}}{c_{2}}}={\frac {A^{2}}{c_{1}}}.$ The above discussion holds true for any component, regardless of its angular frequency of ω.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The limiting case of *c*2 = 0 corresponds to a "fixed end" that does not move, whereas the limiting case of *c*2 → ∞ corresponds to a "free end".
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] A flexible string that is stretched between two points *x* = 0 and *x* = *L* satisfies the wave equation for *t* > 0 and 0 < *x* < *L*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] On the boundary points, u may satisfy a variety of boundary conditions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The case where u is required to vanish at an endpoint (i.e.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] "fixed end") is the limit of this condition when the respective a or b approaches infinity.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This is a special case of the general problem of Sturm–Liouville theory.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] If a and b are positive, the eigenvalues are all positive, and the solutions are trigonometric functions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] A solution that satisfies square-integrable initial conditions for u and *ut* can be obtained from expansion of these functions in the appropriate trigonometric series.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The one-dimensional initial-boundary value theory may be extended to an arbitrary number of space dimensions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Consider a domain D in m-dimensional x space, with boundary B.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Then the wave equation is to be satisfied if x is in D, and *t* > 0.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] where n is the unit outward normal to B, and a is a non-negative function defined on B.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The case where u vanishes on B is a limiting case for a approaching infinity.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This problem may be solved by expanding f and g in the eigenfunctions of the Laplacian in D, which satisfy the boundary conditions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In the case of two space dimensions, the eigenfunctions may be interpreted as the modes of vibration of a drumhead stretched over the boundary B.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] If B is a circle, then these eigenfunctions have an angular component that is a trigonometric function of the polar angle θ, multiplied by a Bessel function (of integer order) of the radial component.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Further details are in Helmholtz equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] If the boundary is a sphere in three space dimensions, the angular components of the eigenfunctions are spherical harmonics, and the radial components are Bessel functions of half-integer order.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The function *s*(*x*, *t*) is often called the source function because in practice it describes the effects of the sources of waves on the medium carrying them.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Physical examples of source functions include the force driving a wave on a string, or the charge or current density in the Lorenz gauge of electromagnetism.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] One method to solve the initial-value problem (with the initial values as posed above) is to take advantage of a special property of the wave equation in an odd number of space dimensions, namely that its solutions respect causality.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] That is, for any point (*xi*, *ti*), the value of *u*(*xi*, *ti*) depends only on the values of *f*(*xi* + *cti*) and *f*(*xi* − *cti*) and the values of the function *g*(*x*) between (*xi* − *cti*) and (*xi* + *cti*).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] This can be seen in d'Alembert's formula, stated above, where these quantities are the only ones that show up in it.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Physically, if the maximum propagation speed is c, then no part of the wave that cannot propagate to a given point by a given time can affect the amplitude at the same point and time.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In terms of finding a solution, this causality property means that for any given point on the line being considered, the only area that needs to be considered is the area encompassing all the points that could causally affect the point being considered.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Denote the area that causally affects point (*xi*, *ti*) as *RC*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The left side is now the sum of three line integrals along the bounds of the causality region.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In the above, the term to be integrated with respect to time disappears because the time interval involved is zero, thus *dt* = 0.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] For the other two sides of the region, it is worth noting that *x* ± *ct* is a constant, namely *xi* ± *cti*, where the sign is chosen appropriately.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] In the last equation of the sequence, the bounds of the integral over the source function have been made explicit.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Looking at this solution, which is valid for all choices (*xi*, *ti*) compatible with the wave equation, it is clear that the first two terms are simply d'Alembert's formula, as stated above as the solution of the homogeneous wave equation in one dimension.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The difference is in the third term, the integral over the source.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] The elastic wave equation (also known as the Navier–Cauchy equation) in three dimensions describes the propagation of waves in an isotropic homogeneous elastic medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Most solid materials are elastic, so this equation describes such phenomena as seismic waves in the Earth and ultrasonic waves used to detect flaws in materials.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] By using ∇ × (∇ × **u**) = ∇(∇ ⋅ **u**) − ∇ ⋅ ∇ **u** = ∇(∇ ⋅ **u**) − ∆**u**, the elastic wave equation can be rewritten into the more common form of the Navier–Cauchy equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Note that in the elastic wave equation, both force and displacement are vector quantities.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] Thus, this equation is sometimes known as the vector wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] As an aid to understanding, the reader will observe that if **f** and ∇ ⋅ **u** are set to zero, this becomes (effectively) Maxwell's equation for the propagation of the electric field **E**, which has only transverse waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-equation] where ω is the angular frequency, and **k** is the wavevector describing plane-wave solutions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In physics, a **wave packet** (also known as a **wave train** or **wave group**) is a short burst of localized wave action that travels as a unit, outlined by an envelope.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] A wave packet can be analyzed into, or can be synthesized from, a potentially-infinite set of component sinusoidal waves of different wavenumbers, with phases and amplitudes such that they interfere constructively only over a small region of space, and destructively elsewhere.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Each component wave function, and hence the wave packet, are solutions of a wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Depending on the wave equation, the wave packet's profile may remain constant (no dispersion) or it may change (dispersion) while propagating.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Ideas related to wave packets – modulation, carrier waves, phase velocity, and group velocity – date from the mid-1800s.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Erwin Schrödinger introduced the idea of wave packets just after publishing his famous wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] He solved his wave equation for a quantum harmonic oscillator, introduced the superposition principle, and used it to show that a compact state could persist.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] While this work did result in the important concept of coherent states, the wave packet concept did not endure.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The year after Schrödinger's paper, Werner Heisenberg published his paper on the uncertainty principle, showing in the process, that Schrödinger's results only applied to quantum harmonic oscillators, not for example to Coulomb potential characteristic of atoms.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The following year, 1927, Charles Galton Darwin explored Schrödinger's equation for an unbound electron in free space, assuming an initial Gaussian wave packet.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] where $\sigma$ is the uncertainty in the initial position.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Later in 1927 Paul Ehrenfest showed that the time, T for a matter wave packet of width $\Delta x$ and mass m to spread by a factor of 2 was ${\textstyle T\approx m{\Delta x}^{2}/\hbar }$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Since $\hbar$ is so small, wave packets on the scale of macroscopic objects, with large width and mass, double only at cosmic time scales.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Quantum mechanics describes the nature of atomic and subatomic systems using Schrödinger's wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The classical limit of quantum mechanics and many formulations of quantum scattering use wave packets formed from various solutions to this equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Quantum wave packet profiles change while propagating; they show dispersion.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Physicists have concluded that "wave packets would not do as representations of subatomic particles".
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Schrodinger developed wave packets in hopes of interpreting quantum wave solutions as locally compact wave groups.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Such packets trade off position localization for spreading momentum.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In the coordinate representation of the wave (such as the Cartesian coordinate system), the position of the particle's localized probability is specified by the position of the packet solution.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The narrower the spatial wave packet, and therefore the better localized the position of the wave packet, the larger the spread in the momentum of the wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] This trade-off between spread in position and spread in momentum is a characteristic feature of the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] One kind of optimal tradeoff minimizes the product of position uncertainty $\Delta x$ and momentum uncertainty $\Delta p_{x}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] If we place such a packet at rest it stays at rest: the average value of the position and momentum match a classical particle.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] However it spreads out in all directions with a velocity given by the optimal momentum uncertainty $\Delta p_{x}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The spread is so fast that in the distance of once around an atom the wave packet is unrecognizable.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Particle interactions are called scattering in physics; the wave packet concept plays an important role in quantum scattering approaches.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] A monochromatic (single momentum) source produces convergence difficulties in the scattering models.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Scattering problems also have classical limits.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Whenever the scattering target (for example an atom) has a size much smaller than wave packet, the center of the wave packet follows scattering classical trajectories.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In other cases, the wave packet distorts and scatters as it interacts with the target.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Without dispersion the wave packet maintains its shape as it propagates.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] where *c* is the speed of the wave's propagation in a given medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] where the relation between the angular frequency *ω* and angular wave vector **k** is given by the dispersion relation: $\omega (\mathbf {k} )=\pm |\mathbf {k} |c=\pm {\frac {2\pi c}{\lambda }},$ such that $\omega ^{2}/|\mathbf {k} |^{2}=c^{2}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] This relation should be valid so that the plane wave is a solution to the wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] As the relation is *linear*, the wave equation is said to be **non-dispersive**.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] To simplify, consider the one-dimensional wave equation with *ω(k)*=*±kc*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Then the general solution is $u(x,t)=Ae^{ik(x-ct)}+Be^{ik(x+ct)},$ where the first and second term represent a wave propagating in the positive respectively negative *x*-direction.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] A wave packet is a localized disturbance that results from the sum of many different wave forms.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] If the packet is strongly localized, more frequencies are needed to allow the constructive superposition in the region of localization and destructive superposition outside the region.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The nondispersive propagation of the real or imaginary part of this wave packet is presented in the above animation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] By contrast, in the case of dispersion, a wave changes shape during propagation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] As the dispersion relation is non-linear, the free Schrödinger equation is **dispersive**.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] If $\psi (\mathbf {r} ,0)$ (and therefore $g(\mathbf {k} )$ ) is a Gaussian function, the wave packet is called a **Gaussian wave packet**.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The inverse Fourier transform is still a Gaussian, but now the parameter a has become complex, and there is an overall normalization factor.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The integral of Ψ over all space is invariant, because it is the inner product of Ψ with the state of zero energy, which is a wave with infinite wavelength, a constant function of space.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] For any energy eigenstate *η*(*x*), the inner product, $\langle \eta |\psi \rangle =\int \eta (\mathbf {r} )\psi (\mathbf {r} )d^{3}\mathbf {r} ,$ only changes in time in a simple way: its phase rotates with a frequency determined by the energy of *η*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] When *η* has zero energy, like the infinite wavelength wave, it doesn't change at all.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] It varies *quadratically* with position, which means that it is different from multiplication by a linear phase factor $e^{i\mathbf {k} \cdot \mathbf {r} }$ as is the case of imparting a constant momentum to the wave packet.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In general, the phase of a gaussian wave packet has both a linear term and a quadratic term.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The coefficient of the quadratic term begins by increasing from $-\infty$ towards 0 as the gaussian wave packet becomes sharper, then at the moment of maximum sharpness, the phase of the wave function varies linearly with position.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Then the coefficient of the quadratic term increases from 0 towards $+\infty$ , as the gaussian wave packet spreads out again.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The integral ∫ |Ψ|2*d*3*r* is also invariant, which is a statement of the conservation of probability.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] For example, if an electron wave packet is initially localized in a region of atomic dimensions (i.e., 10−10 m) then the width of the packet doubles in about 10−16 s.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Clearly, particle wave packets spread out very rapidly indeed (in free space): For instance, after 1 ms, the width will have grown to about a kilometer.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The uncertainty relation is then a strict inequality, very far from saturation, indeed!
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The initial uncertainty Δ*x*Δ*p* = *ħ*/2 has now increased by a factor of *ħt/ma* (for large *t*).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] There is no dissonance with Ehrenfest's theorem in this force-free situation, because the state is both non-normalizable and has an undefined (infinite) ⟨*x*⟩ for all times.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The Airy wave train is the only dispersionless wave in one dimensional free space.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In higher dimensions, other dispersionless waves are possible.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In phase space, this is evident in the pure state Wigner quasiprobability distribution of this wavetrain, whose shape in *x* and *p* is invariant as time progresses, but whose features accelerate to the right, in accelerating parabolas.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The contour lines of the Wigner function are parabolas of form ${\textstyle B\left(x-B^{3}t^{2}\right)+\left(p/B-tB^{2}\right)^{2}=C}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Time-evolution is equivalent to a shearing in phase space along the x -direction at speed $p/m=2p$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Note the momentum distribution obtained by integrating over all x is constant.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Since this is the probability density in momentum space, it is evident that the wave function itself is not normalizable.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The narrow-width limit of the Gaussian wave packet solution discussed is the free propagator kernel K.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] For other differential equations, this is usually called the Green's function, but in quantum mechanics it is traditional to reserve the name Green's function for the time Fourier transform of K.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Note that a very narrow initial wave packet instantly becomes infinitely wide, but with a phase which is more rapidly oscillatory at large values of *x*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] This might seem strange—the solution goes from being localized at one point to being "everywhere" at *all later times*, but it is a reflection of the enormous momentum uncertainty of a localized particle, as explained above.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Further note that the norm of the wave function is infinite, which is also correct, since the square of a delta function is divergent in the same way.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The factor involving ε is an infinitesimal quantity which is there to make sure that integrals over K are well defined.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In the limit that *ε* → 0, K becomes purely oscillatory, and integrals of K are not absolutely convergent.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In the remainder of this section, it *will* be set to zero, but in order for all the integrations over intermediate states to be well defined, the limit *ε*→0 is to be only taken after the final state is calculated.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The propagator is the amplitude for reaching point *x* at time *t*, when starting at the origin, *x*=0.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] In the limit when *t* is small, the propagator goes to a delta function $\lim _{t\to 0}K_{t}(x-y)=\delta (x-y)~,$ but only in the sense of distributions: The integral of this quantity multiplied by an arbitrary differentiable test function gives the value of the test function at zero.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] To see this, note that the integral over all space of K equals 1 at all times, $\int K_{t}(x)dx=1\,,$ since this integral is the inner-product of *K* with the uniform wave function.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] But the phase factor in the exponent has a nonzero spatial derivative everywhere except at the origin, and so when the time is small there are fast phase cancellations at all but one point.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] This is rigorously true when the limit *ε*→0 is taken at the very end.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] So the propagation kernel is the (future) time evolution of a delta function, and it is continuous, in a sense: it goes to the initial delta function at small times.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] Thus, this is a formal way to express the fundamental solution or ***general solution***.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The interpretation of this expression is that the amplitude for a particle to be found at point x at time t is the amplitude that it started at y, times the amplitude that it went from y to x, *summed over all the possible starting points*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] This is a property of an arbitrary quantum system, and by subdividing the time into many segments, it allows the time evolution to be expressed as a path integral.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The spreading of wave packets in quantum mechanics is directly related to the spreading of probability densities in diffusion.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] For a particle which is randomly walking, the probability density function satisfies the diffusion equation ${\partial \over \partial t}\rho ={1 \over 2}{\partial ^{2} \over \partial x^{2}}\rho ,$ where the factor of 2, which can be removed by rescaling either time or space, is only for convenience.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] A solution of this equation is the time-varying Gaussian function $\rho _{t}(x)={1 \over {\sqrt {2\pi t}}}e^{-x^{2} \over 2t},$ which is a form of the heat kernel.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The time-varying Gaussian is the propagation kernel for the diffusion equation and it obeys the convolution identity, $K_{t+t'}=K_{t}*K_{t'}\,,$ which allows diffusion to be expressed as a path integral.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] A matrix has two indices, which in continuous space makes it a function of x and x'.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] The limit of this expression for z approaching the pure imaginary axis is the above Schrödinger propagator encountered, $K_{t}^{\rm {Schr}}=K_{it+\varepsilon }=e^{-(it+\varepsilon )H}\,,$ which illustrates the above time evolution of Gaussians.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave-packet] From the fundamental identity of exponentiation, or path integration, $K_{z}*K_{z'}=K_{z+z'}\,$ holds for all complex *z* values, where the integrals are absolutely convergent so that the operators are well defined.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In mathematics and physical science, a **wave** is a propagating dynamic disturbance (change from equilibrium) of one or more quantities.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] *Periodic waves* oscillate repeatedly about an equilibrium (resting) value at some frequency.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] When the entire waveform moves in one direction, it is said to be a **traveling wave**; by contrast, a pair of identical superimposed periodic waves traveling in opposite directions makes a *standing wave*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In a standing wave, the amplitude of vibration has nulls at some positions where the wave amplitude appears smaller or even zero.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] There are two types of waves that are most commonly studied in classical physics: mechanical waves and electromagnetic waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In a mechanical wave, stress and strain fields oscillate about a mechanical equilibrium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A mechanical wave is a local deformation (strain) in some physical medium that propagates from particle to particle by creating local stresses that cause strain in neighboring particles too.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For example, sound waves are variations of the local pressure and particle motion that propagate through the medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Other examples of mechanical waves are seismic waves, gravity waves, surface waves and string vibrations.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In an electromagnetic wave (such as light), coupling between the electric and magnetic fields sustains propagation of waves involving these fields according to Maxwell's equations.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Electromagnetic waves can travel through a vacuum and through some dielectric media (at wavelengths where they are considered transparent).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Electromagnetic waves, as determined by their frequencies (or wavelengths), have more specific designations including radio waves, infrared radiation, terahertz waves, visible light, ultraviolet radiation, X-rays and gamma rays.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Mechanical and electromagnetic waves transfer energy, momentum and information.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In the case of waves in a liquid medium, matter can also be transferred (see Stokes drift).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In mathematics and electronics waves are studied as signals.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] On the other hand, some waves have envelopes which do not move at all such as standing waves (which are fundamental to music) and hydraulic jumps.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A physical wave field is almost always confined to some finite region of space, called its *domain*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For example, the seismic waves generated by earthquakes are significant only in the interior and surface of the planet, so they can be ignored outside it.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] However, waves with infinite domain, that extend over the whole space, are commonly studied in mathematics, and are very valuable tools for understanding physical waves in finite domains.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A *plane wave* is an important mathematical idealization where the disturbance is identical along any (infinite) plane normal to a specific direction of travel.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Mathematically, the simplest wave is a *sinusoidal plane wave* in which at any point the field experiences simple harmonic motion at one frequency.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In linear media, complicated waves can generally be decomposed as the sum of many sinusoidal plane waves having different directions of propagation and/or different frequencies.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A plane wave is classified as a *transverse wave* if the field disturbance at each point is described by a vector perpendicular to the direction of propagation (also the direction of energy transfer); or *longitudinal wave* if those vectors are aligned with the propagation direction.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Mechanical waves include both transverse and longitudinal waves; on the other hand electromagnetic plane waves are strictly transverse while sound waves in fluids (such as air) can only be longitudinal.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] That physical direction of an oscillating field relative to the propagation direction is also referred to as the wave's *polarization*, which can be an important attribute.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] While waves are ubiquitous features of physical systems, no single definition adequately describes the topic.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Examples and descriptions of common characteristics are used as an alternative to a single definition.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In abstract, waves are the dynamic manifestation of time-dependent field theory analogous to ballistics, the dynamic manifestation of particle mechanics, but this point of view misses the many visually appealing examples of waves like vibrating stringed instruments and fluid ripples.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Viewed microscopically, waves are changes in the value of physical property at a point in space that results from a delayed response to changes in adjacent regions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Examples of properties include pressure, temperature, height, or gravitational force.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A physical medium, like vacuum, air, water, or solid rock may exhibit waves in different properties which may or may not be related.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Properties like the heights spectators at a sporting event or the level of anxiety among political protestors may also be considered waves when the property depends upon delayed responds to physically adjacent events.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In physics, a physical quantity that has a value at points in space is called a field, so a wave is disturbance in a field resulting from delayed response to adjacent disturbances.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Viewed macroscopically, a wave is the dynamic response of a field caused by effects that can only propagate at a finite speed.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Rotation of an electric dipole produce electromagnetic waves and the mutual rotation of binary stars produce gravitational waves, each of which propagate at the speed of light.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Periodic or sinusoidal waves are useful idealized examples, but the essential neighbor-to-neighbor interaction with delay means waves may propagate in non-linear, granular, or noisy media which do not produce these ideal results.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Temperature waves or chemical reaction waves demonstrate that waves need not be a material displacement.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Mathematically, a wave is described by a function $F(x,t)$ that maps a point in space and time onto a field.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For a scalar field its value is a number; for a vector field it is a vector; in general a tensor field has a tensor value.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The value of x is a point of space, specifically in the region where the wave is defined.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In mathematical terms, it is usually a vector in the Cartesian three-dimensional space $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] However, in many cases one can ignore one dimension, and let x be a point of the Cartesian plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This is the case, for example, when studying vibrations of a drum skin.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] One may even restrict x to a point of the Cartesian line $\mathbb {R}$ – that is, the set of real numbers.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This is the case, for example, when studying vibrations in a violin string or recorder.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The time t , on the other hand, is always assumed to be a scalar; that is, a real number.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The value of $F(x,t)$ can be any physical quantity of interest assigned to the point x that may vary with time.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For example, if F represents the vibrations inside an elastic solid, the value of $F(x,t)$ is usually a vector that gives the current displacement from x of the material particles that would be at the point x in the absence of vibration.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For an electromagnetic wave, the value of F can be the electric field vector E , or the magnetic field vector H , or any related quantity, such as the Poynting vector $E\times H$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In fluid dynamics, the value of $F(x,t)$ could be the velocity vector of the fluid at the point x , or any scalar property like pressure, temperature, or density.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In a chemical reaction, $F(x,t)$ could be the concentration of some substance in the neighborhood of point x of the reaction medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For any dimension d (1, 2, or 3), the wave's domain is then a subset D of $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , such that the function value $F(x,t)$ is defined for any point x in D .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For example, when describing the motion of a drum skin, one can consider D to be a disk (circle) on the plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ with center at the origin $(0,0)$ , and let $F(x,t)$ be the vertical displacement of the skin at the point x of D and at time t .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Waves of the same type are often superposed and encountered simultaneously at a given point in space and time.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The properties at that point are the sum of the properties of each component wave at that point.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In general, the velocities are not the same, so the wave form will change over time and space.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A wave spectrum is a representation that describes how the energy of a sea surface (or wave field) is distributed across different wave frequencies (or wave numbers) and directions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Real ocean surfaces consist of many overlapping waves of different wavelengths, periods, amplitudes, and directions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A wave spectrum offers a statistical (spectral) description rather than tracking individual waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The observed sea-surface elevation at a point can be thought of as the sum (superposition) of many sinusoidal wave components; the wave spectrum quantifies how much energy is associated with each component.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Sometimes one is interested in a single specific wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] More often, however, one needs to understand a large set of possible waves; like all the ways that a drum skin can vibrate after being struck once with a drum stick, or all the possible radar echoes one could get from an airplane that may be approaching an airport.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In some of those situations, one may describe such a family of waves by a function $F(A,B,\ldots ;x,t)$ that depends on certain parameters $A,B,\ldots$ , besides x and t .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Then one can obtain different waves – that is, different functions of x and t – by choosing different values for those parameters.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The parameter A defines the amplitude of the wave (that is, the maximum sound pressure in the bore, which is related to the loudness of the note); c is the speed of sound; L is the length of the bore; and n is a positive integer (1,2,3,...) that specifies the number of nodes in the standing wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] (The position x should be measured from the mouthpiece, and the time t from any moment at which the pressure at the mouthpiece is maximum.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The quantity $\lambda =4L/(2n-1)$ is the wavelength of the emitted note, and $f=c/\lambda$ is its frequency.) Many general properties of these waves can be inferred from this general equation, without choosing specific values for the parameters.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] As another example, it may be that the vibrations of a drum skin after a single strike depend only on the distance r from the center of the skin to the strike point, and on the strength s of the strike.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Then the vibration for all possible strikes can be described by a function $F(r,s;x,t)$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Sometimes the family of waves of interest has infinitely many parameters.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For example, one may want to describe what happens to the temperature in a metal bar when it is initially heated at various temperatures at different points along its length, and then allowed to cool by itself in vacuum.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In that case, instead of a scalar or vector, the parameter would have to be a function h such that $h(x)$ is the initial temperature at each point x of the bar.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Another way to describe and study a family of waves is to give a mathematical equation that, instead of explicitly giving the value of $F(x,t)$ , only constrains how those values can change with time.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Then the family of waves in question consists of all functions F that satisfy those constraints – that is, all solutions of the equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This approach is extremely important in physics, because the constraints usually are a consequence of the physical processes that cause the wave to evolve.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This equation can be derived from the laws of physics that govern the diffusion of heat in solid media.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For that reason, it is called the heat equation in mathematics, even though it applies to many other physical quantities besides temperatures.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For another example, we can describe all possible sounds echoing within a container of gas by a function $F(x,t)$ that gives the pressure at a point x and time t within that container.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Here $P(x,t)$ is some extra compression force that is being applied to the gas near x by some external process, such as a loudspeaker or piston right next to it.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This same differential equation describes the behavior of mechanical vibrations and electromagnetic fields in a homogeneous isotropic non-conducting solid.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Note that this equation differs from that of heat flow only in that the left-hand side is $\partial ^{2}F/\partial t^{2}$ , the second derivative of F with respect to time, rather than the first derivative $\partial F/\partial t$ .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Yet this small change makes a huge difference on the set of solutions F .
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This differential equation is called "the" wave equation in mathematics, even though it describes only one very special kind of waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Consider a traveling transverse wave (which may be a pulse) on a string (the medium).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Consider the string to have a single spatial dimension.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] or, more generally, by d'Alembert's formula: $u(x,t)=F(x-vt)+G(x+vt).$ representing two component waveforms F and G traveling through the medium in opposite directions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] General solutions are based upon Duhamel's principle.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The form or shape of *F* in d'Alembert's formula involves the argument *x* − *vt*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Constant values of this argument correspond to constant values of *F*, and these constant values occur if *x* increases at the same rate that *vt* increases.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] That is, the wave shaped like the function *F* will move in the positive *x*-direction at velocity *v* (and *G* will propagate at the same speed in the negative *x*-direction).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In the case of a periodic function *F* with period *λ*, that is, *F*(*x* + *λ* − *vt*) = *F*(*x* − *vt*), the periodicity of *F* in space means that a snapshot of the wave at a given time *t* finds the wave varying periodically in space with period *λ* (the wavelength of the wave).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In a similar fashion, this periodicity of *F* implies a periodicity in time as well: *F*(*x* − *v*(*t* + *T*)) = *F*(*x* − *vt*) provided *vT* = *λ*, so an observation of the wave at a fixed location *x* finds the wave undulating periodically in time with period *T* = *λ*/*v*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The amplitude of a wave may be constant (in which case the wave is a *c.w.* or *continuous wave*), or may be *modulated* so as to vary with time and/or position.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The outline of the variation in amplitude is called the *envelope* of the wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Mathematically, the modulated wave can be written in the form: $u(x,t)=A(x,t)\sin \left(kx-\omega t+\phi \right),$ where $A(x,\ t)$ is the amplitude envelope of the wave, k is the *wavenumber* and $\phi$ is the *phase*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] If the group velocity $v_{g}$ (see below) is wavelength-independent, this equation can be simplified as: $u(x,t)=A(x-v_{g}t)\sin \left(kx-\omega t+\phi \right),$ showing that the envelope moves with the group velocity and retains its shape.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Otherwise, in cases where the group velocity varies with wavelength, the pulse shape changes in a manner often described using an *envelope equation*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] There are two velocities that are associated with waves, the phase velocity and the group velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Phase velocity is the rate at which the phase of the wave propagates in space: any given phase of the wave (for example, the crest) will appear to travel at the phase velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Group velocity is a property of waves that have a defined envelope, measuring propagation through space (that is, phase velocity) of the overall shape of the waves' amplitudes—modulation or envelope of the wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A sine wave, sinusoidal wave, or sinusoid (symbol: ∿) is a periodic wave whose waveform (shape) is the trigonometric sine function.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In mechanics, as a linear motion over time, this is *simple harmonic motion*; as rotation, it corresponds to *uniform circular motion*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Sine waves occur often in physics, including wind waves, sound waves, and light waves, such as monochromatic radiation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In engineering, signal processing, and mathematics, Fourier analysis decomposes general functions into a sum of sine waves of various frequencies, relative phases, and magnitudes.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] When any two sine waves of the same frequency (but arbitrary phase) are linearly combined, the result is another sine wave of the same frequency; this property is unique among periodic waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Conversely, if some phase is chosen as a zero reference, a sine wave of arbitrary phase can be written as the linear combination of two sine waves with phases of zero and a quarter cycle, the *sine* and *cosine* components, respectively.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A plane wave is a kind of wave whose value varies only in one spatial direction.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] That is, its value is constant on a plane that is perpendicular to that direction.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Plane waves can be specified by a vector of unit length ${\hat {n}}$ indicating the direction that the wave varies in, and a wave profile describing how the wave varies as a function of the displacement along that direction ( ${\hat {n}}\cdot {\vec {x}}$ ) and time ( t ).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Since the wave profile only depends on the position ${\vec {x}}$ in the combination ${\hat {n}}\cdot {\vec {x}}$ , any displacement in directions perpendicular to ${\hat {n}}$ cannot affect the value of the field.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Plane waves are often used to model electromagnetic waves far from a source.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For electromagnetic plane waves, the electric and magnetic fields themselves are transverse to the direction of propagation, and also perpendicular to each other.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A standing wave, also known as a *stationary wave*, is a wave whose envelope remains in a constant position.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This phenomenon arises as a result of interference between two waves traveling in opposite directions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The *sum* of two counter-propagating waves (of equal amplitude and frequency) creates a *standing wave*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Standing waves commonly arise when a boundary blocks further propagation of the wave, thus causing wave reflection, and therefore introducing a counter-propagating wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For example, when a violin string is displaced, transverse waves propagate out to where the string is held in place at the bridge and the nut, where the waves are reflected back.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] At the bridge and nut, the two opposed waves are in antiphase and cancel each other, producing a node.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Halfway between two nodes there is an antinode, where the two counter-propagating waves *enhance* each other maximally.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] There is no net propagation of energy over time.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A **soliton** or **solitary wave** is a self-reinforcing wave packet that maintains its shape while it propagates at a constant velocity.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Solitons are caused by a cancellation of nonlinear and dispersive effects in the medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] (Dispersive effects are a property of certain systems where the speed of a wave depends on its frequency.) Solitons are the solutions of a widespread class of weakly nonlinear dispersive partial differential equations describing physical systems.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Wave propagation is any of the ways in which waves travel.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] With respect to the direction of the oscillation relative to the propagation direction, we can distinguish between longitudinal wave and transverse waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Electromagnetic waves propagate in vacuum as well as in material media.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Propagation of other wave types such as sound may occur only in a transmission medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The propagation and reflection of plane waves—e.g.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Pressure waves (P wave) or Shear waves (SH or SV-waves) are phenomena that were first characterized within the field of classical seismology, and are now considered fundamental concepts in modern seismic tomography.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The analytical solution to this problem exists and is well known.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The frequency domain solution can be obtained by first finding the Helmholtz decomposition of the displacement field, which is then substituted into the wave equation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] From here, the plane wave eigenmodes can be calculated.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The analytical solution of SV-wave in a half-space indicates that the plane SV wave reflects back to the domain as a P and SV waves, leaving out special cases.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The angle of the reflected SV wave is identical to the incidence wave, while the angle of the reflected P wave is greater than the SV wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For the same wave frequency, the SV wavelength is smaller than the P wavelength.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This fact has been depicted in this animated picture.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Similar to the SV wave, the P incidence, in general, reflects as the P and SV wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] There are some special cases where the regime is different.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Wave velocity is a general concept, of various kinds of wave velocities, for a wave's phase and speed concerning energy (and information) propagation.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The phase speed gives you the speed at which a point of constant phase of the wave will travel for a discrete frequency.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In the special case Ω(*k*) = *ck*, with *c* a constant, the waves are called non-dispersive, since all frequencies travel at the same phase speed *c*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For instance electromagnetic waves in vacuum are non-dispersive.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In case of other forms of the dispersion relation, we have dispersive waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The dispersion relationship depends on the medium through which the waves propagate and on the type of waves (for instance electromagnetic, sound or water waves).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In almost all cases, a wave is mainly a movement of energy through a medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Most often, the group velocity is the velocity at which the energy moves through this medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Waves normally move in a straight line (that is, rectilinearly) through a *transmission medium*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Waves are usually defined in media which allow most or all of a wave's energy to propagate without loss.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] However materials may be characterized as "lossy" if they remove energy from a wave, usually converting it into heat.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This is termed "absorption." A material which absorbs a wave's energy, either in transmission or reflection, is characterized by a refractive index which is complex.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The amount of absorption will generally depend on the frequency (wavelength) of the wave, which, for instance, explains why objects may appear colored.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] When a wave strikes a reflective surface, it changes direction, such that the angle made by the incident wave and line normal to the surface equals the angle made by the reflected wave and the same normal line.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Refraction is the phenomenon of a wave changing its speed.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Mathematically, this means that the size of the phase velocity changes.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Typically, refraction occurs when a wave passes from one medium into another.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The amount by which a wave is refracted by a material is given by the refractive index of the material.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The directions of incidence and refraction are related to the refractive indices of the two materials by Snell's law.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A wave exhibits diffraction when it encounters an obstacle that bends the wave or when it spreads after emerging from an opening.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Diffraction effects are more pronounced when the size of the obstacle or opening is comparable to the wavelength of the wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] When waves in a linear medium (the usual case) cross each other in a region of space, they do not actually interact with each other, but continue on as if the other one were not present.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] However at any point *in* that region the *field quantities* describing those waves add according to the superposition principle.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] If the waves are of the same frequency in a fixed phase relationship, then there will generally be positions at which the two waves are *in phase* and their amplitudes *add*, and other positions where they are *out of phase* and their amplitudes (partially or fully) *cancel*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The phenomenon of polarization arises when wave motion can occur simultaneously in two orthogonal directions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Transverse waves can be polarized, for instance.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] When polarization is used as a descriptor without qualification, it usually refers to the special, simple case of linear polarization.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A transverse wave is linearly polarized if it oscillates in only one direction or plane.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In the case of linear polarization, it is often useful to add the relative orientation of that plane, perpendicular to the direction of travel, in which the oscillation occurs, such as "horizontal" for instance, if the plane of polarization is parallel to the ground.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Electromagnetic waves propagating in free space, for instance, are transverse; they can be polarized by the use of a polarizing filter.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Longitudinal waves, such as sound waves, do not exhibit polarization.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For these waves there is only one direction of oscillation, that is, along the direction of travel.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Dispersion is the frequency dependence of the refractive index, a consequence of the atomic nature of materials.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A wave undergoes dispersion when either the phase velocity or the group velocity depends on the wave frequency.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Dispersion is seen by letting white light pass through a prism, the result of which is to produce the spectrum of colors of the rainbow.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Isaac Newton was the first to recognize that this meant that white light was a mixture of light of different colors.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The Doppler effect or Doppler shift is the change in frequency of a wave in relation to an observer who is moving relative to the wave source.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] It is named after the Austrian physicist Christian Doppler, who described the phenomenon in 1842.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A mechanical wave is an oscillation of matter, and therefore transfers energy through a medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] While waves can move over long distances, the movement of the medium of transmission—the material—is limited.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Therefore, the oscillating material does not move far from its initial position.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Mechanical waves can be produced only in media which possess elasticity and inertia.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] There are three types of mechanical waves: transverse waves, longitudinal waves, and surface waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The transverse vibration of a string is a function of tension and inertia, and is constrained by the length of the string as the ends are fixed.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This constraint limits the steady state modes that are possible, and thereby the frequencies.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] where the linear density *μ* is the mass per unit length of the string.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Acoustic or sound waves are compression waves that propagate through gases, liquids, solids and plasmas.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] or the square root of the adiabatic bulk modulus divided by the ambient density of the medium (see speed of sound).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Gravity waves are waves generated in a fluid medium or at the interface between two media when the force of gravity or buoyancy works to restore equilibrium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Surface waves on water are the most familiar example.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Body waves travel through the interior of the medium along paths controlled by the material properties in terms of density and modulus (stiffness).
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The density and modulus, in turn, vary according to temperature, composition, and material phase.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This effect resembles the refraction of light waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Two types of particle motion result in two types of body waves: Primary and Secondary waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Seismic waves are waves of energy that travel through the Earth's layers, and are a result of earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, magma movement, large landslides and large man-made explosions that give out low-frequency acoustic energy.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] They include body waves—the primary (P waves) and secondary waves (S waves)—and surface waves, such as Rayleigh waves, Love waves, and Stoneley waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] A shock wave is a type of propagating disturbance.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] When a wave moves faster than the local speed of sound in a fluid, it is a shock wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Like an ordinary wave, a shock wave carries energy and can propagate through a medium; however, it is characterized by an abrupt, nearly discontinuous change in pressure, temperature and density of the medium.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Shear waves are body waves due to shear rigidity and inertia.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] They can only be transmitted through solids and to a lesser extent through liquids with a sufficiently high viscosity.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Gravitational waves also travel through space.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The first observation of gravitational waves was announced on 11 February 2016.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Gravitational waves are disturbances in the curvature of spacetime, predicted by Einstein's theory of general relativity.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] An electromagnetic wave consists of two waves that are oscillations of the electric and magnetic fields.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] An electromagnetic wave travels in a direction that is at right angles to the oscillation direction of both fields.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In the 19th century, James Clerk Maxwell showed that, in vacuum, the electric and magnetic fields satisfy the wave equation both with speed equal to that of the speed of light.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] From this emerged the idea that light is an electromagnetic wave.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The unification of light and electromagnetic waves was experimentally confirmed by Hertz in the end of the 1880s.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Electromagnetic waves can have different frequencies (and thus wavelengths), and are classified accordingly in wavebands, such as radio waves, microwaves, infrared, visible light, ultraviolet, X-rays, and gamma rays.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The range of frequencies in each of these bands is continuous, and the limits of each band are mostly arbitrary, with the exception of visible light, which must be visible to the normal human eye.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The Schrödinger equation describes the wave-like behavior of particles in quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Solutions of this equation are wave functions which can be used to describe the probability density of a particle.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The Dirac equation is a relativistic wave equation detailing electromagnetic interactions.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Dirac waves accounted for the fine details of the hydrogen spectrum in a completely rigorous way.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The wave equation also implied the existence of a new form of matter, antimatter, previously unsuspected and unobserved and which was experimentally confirmed.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In the context of quantum field theory, the Dirac equation is reinterpreted to describe quantum fields corresponding to spin-1⁄2 particles.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] where *h* is the Planck constant, and *p* is the magnitude of the momentum of the particle.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] This hypothesis was at the basis of quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Nowadays, this wavelength is called the de Broglie wavelength.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] For example, the electrons in a CRT display have a de Broglie wavelength of about 10−13 m.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] However, a wave like this with definite wavelength is not localized in space, and so cannot represent a particle localized in space.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] To localize a particle, de Broglie proposed a superposition of different wavelengths ranging around a central value in a wave packet, a waveform often used in quantum mechanics to describe the wave function of a particle.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In a wave packet, the wavelength of the particle is not precise, and the local wavelength deviates on either side of the main wavelength value.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] In representing the wave function of a localized particle, the wave packet is often taken to have a Gaussian shape and is called a *Gaussian wave packet*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] Gaussian wave packets also are used to analyze water waves.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] at some initial time *t* = 0, where the central wavelength is related to the central wave vector *k*0 as *λ*0 = 2π / *k*0.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The Fourier transform of a Gaussian is itself a Gaussian.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] that is, a number of waves of wavelengths *λ* such that *kλ* = 2 π.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] The parameter σ decides the spatial spread of the Gaussian along the *x*-axis, while the Fourier transform shows a spread in wave vector *k* determined by 1/*σ*.
[src:wave-mechanics/wave] That is, the smaller the extent in space, the larger the extent in *k*, and hence in *λ* = 2π/*k*.
